# No one-letter identifiers

Do not use **single-letter** names for variables, function parameters, or catch bindings. Names should communicate role (e.g. `event`, `error`, `index`, `rawValue`).

## Allowed

- **`_`** only as a **discard** placeholder (e.g. `array.map((_, index) => index)`), matching ESLint `id-length` exceptions.
- **`i`**, **`j`**, **`k`** only as **classic `for` loop** index variables (`for (let i = 0; …)`, nested loops). Do not use them elsewhere when a longer name is clearer; ESLint cannot restrict these names to loops only, so rely on convention.
- **Type parameters** in generics may stay conventional single letters when standard (`T`, `K`, `V`) only if the team agrees; prefer a short **word** (`TItem`, `TResult`) when clarity helps.

## ❌ Bad

```ts
const t = clamp(x / y, 0, 1);
items.map((a, b) => a + b);
} catch (e) {
  console.warn(e);
}
```

## ✅ Good

```ts
const scrollProgress = clamp(scrollY / viewportHeight, 0, 1);
items.map((left, right) => left + right);
} catch (error) {
  console.warn(error);
}

for (let rowIndex = 0; rowIndex < rows; rowIndex++) {
  for (let columnIndex = 0; columnIndex < cols; columnIndex++) {
    // ...
  }
}
// or, when a single-letter index is idiomatic:
for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < m; j++) {
    matrix[i][j] = 0;
  }
}
```

## Enforcement

ESLint `id-length` is enabled in `eslint.config.mjs` (`min: 2`, `exceptions: ["_", "i", "j", "k"]`, `properties: "never"`).
